    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1927-12-06T10:44:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1927-12-06T10:44:00-05:00" n="205"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d205">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">811.7482/13: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Minister in Liberia</hi> (<persName type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Francis</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Monrovia</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1927-12-06T15:00:00-00:44">
                            <hi rend="italic">December 6, 1927—3 p.m.</hi>
                        </date>
                        <lb/>[Received December 7—4:35 p.m.]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>53. The Department’s number 53, December 3, 3 p.m. Liberian Government’s position
                    as follows: <list>
                        <label>[1.]</label>
                        <item>Concedes right internal communication but: <list>
                                <label>(1)</label>
                                <item>Transatlantic short wave neither known nor contemplated by
                                    parties when agreement signed;</item>
                                <label>(2)</label>
                                <item>Government’s experiments having proved successful see no
                                    reason why Firestone should reap benefits;</item>
                                <label>(3)</label>
                                <item>Why if regarded as rights under the concession did Firestone
                                    Junior year ago verbally sound out Barclay <hi rend="italic"
                                        >re</hi> operation trans-Atlantic station and local counsel
                                    in present issue first sound out Cabinet for permit? Government
                                    adamant in this position but probably receptive to special rate
                                    agreement, more economical for Firestone than erection
                                    station.</item>
                            </list>
                        </item>
                        <label>2.</label>
                        <item>Foreign application for Liberian concessions now pending, present time
                            inopportune to force issue. Insistence will seriously antagonize public
                            opinion. Amicable adjustment through good offices Legation will be made
                            difficult by failure Firestone fulfill promises to Liberian Government.
                            See unofficial note Macy<note n="34" xml:id="d205fn34">Clarence E. Macy,
                                vice consul and third secretary at Monrovia, Apr. 18, 1927, to Nov.
                                17, 1927.</note> to Castle,<note n="35" xml:id="d205fn35">William R.
                                Castle, Jr., Assistant Secretary of State.</note> October 10th.<note
                                n="36" xml:id="d205fn36">Note not found in Department files.</note>
                        </item>
                    </list>
                </p>
                <p rend="center">. . . . . . . . . . . . . .</p>
                <p>Until certain Department understands peculiar situation reluctant proceed tender
                    good offices. Please instruct.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Francis</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
